07091nam a22007935i 9780226044316DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20081990ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780226044316  a(DE-B1597)535586  a(OCoLC)781253700  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aHC106.3.C714 vol. 54 7aBUS0000002bisacsh04a330 sa339.400aFifty Years of Economic Measurement :bThe Jubilee of the Conference on Research in Income and Wealth /ced. by Ernst R. Berndt, Jack E. Triplett. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2008] 4c©1990  a1 online resource (464 p.) :b55 tables, 5 figures  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNational Bureau of Economic Research Studies in Income and Wealth ;v5400tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPrefatory Note -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Conference on Research in Income and Wealth: The Early Years -- t2. Luncheon in Honor of Individuals and Institutions Participating in the First Income and Wealth Conference (December 1936-January 1937) -- t3. Productivity and Economic Growth -- t4. The Measurement of Capital -- t5. Issues in the Measurement and Interpretation of Saving and Wealth -- t6. Hedonic Price Indexes and the Measurement of Capital and Productivity : Some Historical Reflections -- t7. Hedonic Methods in Statistical Agency Environments: An Intellectual Biopsy -- t8. The Measurement of Construction Prices: Retrospect and Prospect -- t9. Data Difficulties in Labor Economics -- t10. Demands for Data and Analysis Induced by Environmental Policy -- t11. Measuring Tax Burden: A Historical Perspective -- t12. Policy Users’ Panel -- tAddresses of Contributors -- tAuthor Index -- tSubject Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis volume contains papers presented at a conference in May 1988 in Washington, D.C., commemorating the fiftieth anniversary of the founding of the Conference on Research in Income and Wealth (CRIW). The call for papers emphasized assessments of broad topics in economic measurement, both conceptual and pragmatic. The organizers desired (and succeeded in obtaining) a mix of papers that, first, illustrate the range of measurement issues that economics as a science must confront and, second, mark major milestones of CRIW accomplishment. The papers concern prices and output (Griliches, Pieper, Triplett) and also the major productive inputs, capital (Hulten) and labor (Hamermesh). Measures of saving, the source of capital accumulation, are covered in one paper (Boskin); measuring productivity, the source of much of the growth in per capita income, is reviewed in another (Jorgenson). The use of economic data in economic policy analysis and in regulation are illustrated in a review of measures of tax burden (Atrostic and Nunns) and in an analysis of the data needed for environmental regulation (Russell and Smith); the adequacy of data for policy analysis is evaluated in a roundtable discussion (chapter 12) involving four distinguished policy analysts with extensive government experience in Washington and Ottawa.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aBusiness. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / General.2bisacsh  aeconomy, conference, research, academic, scholarly, higher ed, textbook, educational, income, wealth, finance, financial, economics, poverty, 1980s, history, historical, washington dc, anniversary, criw, science, griliches, pieper, triplett, production, productivity, capital, hulten, labor, output, hamermesh, saing, boskin, data, analysis, regulation, tax.1 aAtrostic, B. K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerndt, Ernst R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerndt, Ernst R., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.g